        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Liverpool</placeName>
                <date>Sept. 9th 1852</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I have to acknowledge the receipt of your<lb/> esteem'd letter with
                the enclosed sheets of your intended Bible.<lb/> I like it very much &amp; wish you
                much success: but wishing without<lb/> acting will not tend furthering your views. I
                    <sic>havegiven</sic> them to my<lb/> friend <persName>Em. Mocatta</persName>—who
                has kindly promised to shew them to his<lb/> friends in
                    <placeName>London</placeName>. Will you please to put my name down for a copy—<lb/>
                <persName>Mrs. L. H. Samuel.</persName> one copy—<persName>Mr. Sylvester L.
                    Samuel</persName>—one copy<lb/> I have &amp; shall speak of it whenever
                opportunity offers. I<lb/> perfectly agree with you that a proper translation of <hi
                    rend="underline">our</hi> holy<lb/> Bible ought and should be had for our Youth
                in order that they<lb/> might not be led astray from the bias which the old
                translators had<lb/> in the olden time—probably when you have completed your great
                work<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">cheap edition</hi> for the use of schools would be
                productive of in-<lb/>calcuable good and greatly promotive of our Holy faith * Your
                Ideas<lb/> of offerings &amp; Blessings (for money) in our Synagogues meet with
                my<lb/> entire approbation. I believe I was the first in
                    <placeName>Liverpool</placeName> to<lb/> strike a blow at the System &amp; I
                have invariably declined offering<lb/> for some years past. I have not the least
                objection to contribute<lb/> my full share for the support of its officers by an
                assessment. &amp; in<lb/> answer to those opposed to my views &amp; will not
                contribute by by a<lb/> public display of their charity I will give them such
                display: if<lb/> they will send their donations. I will publish them in print
                every<lb/> year and circulate them not only in our immediate community but
                through<lb/> the world in our yearly account current as the donation of
                    <persName>Mr. So &amp; So.</persName><lb/> first donation—Second do—third
                do—&amp; so on so that all may know<lb/> their munificence: But no mention of <hi
                    rend="underline">Mammon</hi> in the <hi rend="underline">House of God</hi>.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I can't stand to hear a worthless irreligious Bad man called to the<lb/> Sefer and
                crave from the Almighty a blessing for <hi rend="underline">me</hi> for which
                he<lb/> offers—12 Cents!! (or 6 pence). I won't have it &amp; please God<lb/> shall
                do all in my power to abolish the system.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Wishing you a Happy New Year,</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I remain, Rev. Sir.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">Very Respectfully.</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Lewis Samuel</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Please to put my name down for two copies of
                    <persName>Dias'</persName> Letters</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your Ideas of offerings &amp; Blessings (for money)<lb/> in our
                Synagogues meet with my entire approbation.<lb/> I believe I was the first in
                    <placeName>Liverpool</placeName> to strike a<lb/> blow at the System &amp; I
                have invariably declined offer-<lb/>ing for some years past. I have not the least
                objec-<lb/>tion to contribute my full share for the support of<lb/> its officers by
                an assessment. &amp; in answer to those<lb/> opposed to my views &amp; will not
                contribute but by a<lb/> public display of their charity I will give them such<lb/>
                display: if they will send their donations. I will pub-<lb/>lish them in print every
                year and circulate them not only<lb/> in our immediate community but through the
                world in our<lb/> yearly account current as the donation of <persName>Mr. So &amp;
                    So.</persName><lb/> first donation—Second do—third do— &amp; so on so that
                all<lb/> may know their munificence: But no mention of <hi rend="underline"
                    >Mammon</hi><lb/> in the <hi rend="underline">House of God.</hi> I can't stand
                to hear a worthless<lb/> irreligious Bad man called to the Sefer and crave from<lb/>
                the Almighty a blessing for <hi rend="underline">me</hi> for which he offers —<lb/>
                12 Cents!! (or 6 pence). I won't have it &amp; please God<lb/> shall do all in my
                power to abolish the system.</p>
            <p>From letter of <persName role="author">Lewis Samuel</persName> of
                    <placeName>Liverpool</placeName>, dated <date>Sept. 9th, 1852</date> to
                    <persName>I. L.</persName></p>
